Susan Sarandon</link> to play the Marilyn Monroe character.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref> Sarandon declined the lead role with the query, "Why should I perpetuate someone else's legend when I should be creating my own?"<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref></p>
<p>

On March 7, 1983, the <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../027/417027.xml">
American Repertory Theatre</link></institution>
</company>
 at <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/18426501.xml">
Harvard University</link></university>
 in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../685/5685.xml">
Cambridge, Massachusetts</link></village>
, where Mailer is an <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../412/18951412.xml">
alumni</link>, presented a staged reading of <it>Strawhead.</it><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2211%22])">11</ref> The presentation was part of the theaters noted Monday night series at the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../027/417027.xml">
Loeb Drama Center</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2211%22])">11</ref> <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../027/417027.xml">
ART</link></institution>
</company>
 actor Karen MacDonald played the lead role.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref> At this point, the play was an unproduced <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../521/7697521.xml">
spec script</link>,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2211%22])">11</ref> Mailer thought the play needed trimming,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref> and there were no immediate plans to produce <it>Strawhead.</it><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref></p>
<p>

In June 1983, it was announced that <it>Strawhead</it> would be produced by <link>
Marshall Oglesby</link> at <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../628/12331628.xml">
Provincetown Playhouse</link> in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../470/45470.xml">
Manhattan</link></village>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2212%22])">12</ref> At Mailer's recommendation, Oglesby selected <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../027/417027.xml">
ART</link></institution>
</company>
 actor Karen MacDonald to play the Monroe character.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2213%22])">13</ref><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2214%22])">14</ref> In late August 1983, <it>Strawhead</it> was presented at <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../628/12331628.xml">
Provincetown Playhouse</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2213%22])">13</ref></p>
<p>

In November 1985, Mailer brought his play to the <school wordnetid="108276720" confidence="0.8">
<educational_institution wordnetid="108276342" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../560/437560.xml">
Actors Studio</link></institution>
</educational_institution>
</school>
,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> an <dramatic_composition wordnetid="107007684" confidence="0.8">
<play wordnetid="107007945" confidence="0.8">
<written_communication wordnetid="106349220" confidence="0.8">
<writing wordnetid="106362953" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../127/89127.xml">
Off Broadway</link></writing>
</written_communication>
</play>
</dramatic_composition>
 theater and school that gained worldwide recognition under the leadership of <actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../438/572438.xml">
Lee Strasberg</link></actor>
. The scenes presented were <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../443/425443.xml">
workshop</link> scenes<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2215%22])">15</ref> and Mailer put himself in position of director of the two-act production.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> In addition to the cast including Robert Heller, Mickey Knox and Patrick Sullivan, Mailer added his wife Norris Church to the cast.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> There was no admission charge to the workshop.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref></p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Debut and aftermath</st>
<p>

In January 1986, <it>Strawhead</it> was debuted in full at the Actors Studio,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2215%22])">15</ref> with actor and playwright <link>
John Jiler</link> playing Mr. Charles.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2216%22])">16</ref> American playwright and critic <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<communicator wordnetid="109610660" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<traveler wordnetid="109629752" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<exile wordnetid="110071332" confidence="0.8">
<writer wordnetid="110794014" confidence="0.8">
<dramatist wordnetid="110030277" confidence="0.8">
<absentee wordnetid="109757653" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../882/3441882.xml">
Bonnie Greer</link></absentee>
</dramatist>
</writer>
</exile>
</causal_agent>
</traveler>
</person>
</communicator>
</physical_entity>
, who shared a close relationship to Mailer and reviewed an initial version of the play, stated that what Mailer put on stage ultimately was not Monroe.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%228%22])">8</ref> Rather, the play was more about "chronicling all Mailer's life as The Great, White, Male Heterosexual, "Big Daddy", "The Man.""<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%228%22])">8</ref></p>
<p>

<image location="right" width="150px" src="VanityFairApril1986Cover.JPG" type="thumb">
<caption>

April 1986 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../121/40121.xml">
Vanity Fair</link> cover presenting <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../037/23037.xml">
punk rocker</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../774/14228774.xml">
Kate Mailer</link> in <it>Strawhead</it> as <person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9173553029164789">
<playmate wordnetid="110441037" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../318/19318.xml">
Marilyn Monroe</link></playmate>
</actor>
</person>
.
</caption>
</image>

In April 1986, it was first reported that Mailer's daughter <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../774/14228774.xml">
Kate Mailer</link> was added to the cast in the lead role.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%224%22])">4</ref> The choice was in interesting one since the play characterizes a fictional interaction between Monroe and Mailer and an early draft had a clichéd Monroe giving a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../258/11258.xml">
blowjob</link> to the Mailer-interviewer character.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%228%22])">8</ref> In explaining Mailer's choice of casting his 23-year-old, unknown actress daughter in his play, Mailer stated, "She was the best <link>
prep-school</link> actress I'd ever seen."<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%224%22])">4</ref> To bring publicity to the play and to sell the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../121/40121.xml">
Vanity Fair</link> magazine, Kate Mailer appeared on the April 1986 Vanity Fair cover as the Marilyn Monroe character in <it>Strawhead</it>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%224%22])">4</ref> In October 1987, the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../680/30680.xml">
New York Times</link> describe Kate Mailer's portrayal of Monroe as teenage <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../037/23037.xml">
punk rocker</link> who is "less identified with her role."<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2217%22])">17</ref></p>
<p>

After the 1986 performances, the commercial performance of <it>Strawhead</it> all but disappeared.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2218%22])">18</ref> In her 2005 book <it>The Many Lives of Marilyn Monroe,</it> author <link>
Sarah Churchwell</link> notes that <it>Strawhead</it> was a commercial failure.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2218%22])">18</ref></p>
<p>

In April 2008, <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/18426501.xml">
Harvard University</link></university>
 received the papers of the co-author of the play, Richard G. Hannum,<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2219%22])">19</ref> formerly a resident of <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../265/109265.xml">
Sebastian, Florida</link></village>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2220%22])">20</ref> Included with those papers were correspondence with Mailer and drafts and final script for <it>Strawhead</it>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2219%22])">19</ref> The drafts and final script evidence the <artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<device wordnetid="103183080" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../761/65761.xml">
literary techniques</link></device>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
 used in <it>Strawhead</it> and Mailer's efforts to continually improve his own writing for <it>Strawhead</it> and that of Hannums.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2219%22])">19</ref> Importantly, they convey research and teaching about how the style and substance of <it>Strawhead</it> was developed through layers of revision.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%2219%22])">19</ref></p>

